```java
public static Vector3D crossProduct(final Vector3D v1, final Vector3D v2) {
    // compute rho as an 8 bits approximation of v1.v2 / v2.v2
    double dot = v1.x * v2.x + v1.y * v2.y + v1.z * v2.z;
    double normSq = v2.x * v2.x + v2.y * v2.y + v2.z * v2.z;
    double rho = (dot / normSq);
    // approximate rho to 8 bits
    rho = Math.floor(rho * 256) / 256; // truncation? Actually, to have an 8-bit approximation, we can use floor or rint.
    // I'll use rint for rounding.
    // But we need to preserve the sign.
    // Let's use: rho = (double)( (long)(rho * 256) ) / 256; // truncate
    // Actually, the exact method from Kahan: compute rho as (int)(dot/normSq * 256) / 256.0? Wait: he uses integer arithmetic to get an 8-bit approximation.
    // Let's implement as:
    // double approx = Math.rint(dot / normSq * 256) / 256;
    // This gives the nearest multiple of 1/256.
    
    double approx = Math.rint(dot / normSq * 256) / 256;
    // compute v3 = v1 - approx * v2
    double c1 = v1.x - approx * v2.x;
    double c2 = v1.y - approx * v2.y;
    double c3 = v1.z - approx * v2.z;
    // cross product of v3 and v2
    return new Vector3D(c2 * v2.z - c3 * v2.y,
                        c3 * v2.x - c1 * v2.z,
                        c1 * v2.y - c2 * v2.x);
}
```

